\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for integrating new and better methodologies for learning derived from worldwide
 research or culled from the vast database of performance created by this
 system.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Description
Homework: There is no requirement for homework in this system though students
 may be encouraged to do projects and produce a portfolio for employers
 and universities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Textbooks: There are no textbooks required for students on this project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
MOOCs: Many elite universities are today providing educational modules on
 subjects varying from artificial intelligence to entrepreneurship through
 the medium of Massive Online Open Courses (MOOCs).
 The defining characteristic required to take advantage of this invaluable
 resource is a meaningful education in the teenage years.
 I believe that students graduating from schools deploying the AGEM method
 will be ideal populations to take advantage of the opportunities that MOOCs
 generate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
How will impact be measured?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the past we have used placement tests developed and tested in the United
 States for the purpose of measuring academic impact and we will continue
 to do this.
 Past experience has shown that Grade 6 students are below the average level
 of Grade 3 placement tests both in English and Maths.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Additionally, in this case, we hope to invoke the expertise of the Harvard
 Graduate School of Education to conduct independent testing for academic
 impact.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We also expect to test the impact on the sense of well being of the children.
 For this we intend to use Seligman's CASQ
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Children's Attributional Style Questionnaire
\end_layout

\end_inset

, WHO-5 and the WEMWBS tests which represent established methods of measurement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In addition, the embedded questions in the topic plans are also used for
 measurement of student response and progress over the duration of the course.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Finally, we measure changes in the end of term examinations prior to the
 program and those taken at the end of the program.
 This demonstrates that our students have learned how to learn and will
 therefore see an overall improvement across the board.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
What is the overall design of the study
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Selection of students
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While we expect to test the full set of Grades 6, 7 and 8 for the study,
 we will select half the full set to form the experimental group while the
 remainder become the control group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Pre and Post testing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following tests are envisaged both before the start of the course and
 at the end of the course:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Placement tests for English and Maths conducted by us.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Specific tests for Systems Thinking
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Tests of explanatory style such as CASQ, WHO-5, and WEMWBS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Conduct of the course
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We expect to conduct this for about 3 hours on Saturday's and about 2 hours
 at one other day in the week.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The topics covered include English, Maths and Systems Thinking.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The approach is generally interdisciplinary so a topic plan may cover all
 three disciplines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We generally prefer longer classes to avoid the wastage of time that is
 involved in start up processes.
 Our experience has been that students can take our classes for 5 to 6 hours
 at a time with short breaks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We expect students to work on collaborative projects using computers and
 open source software as this is an important element of real-world environments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
What are the technology aspects of the project?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Technology in terms of hardware and software is deployed as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Feedback
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

devices: Our fourth generation proprietary feedback devices are wireless
 transceivers interfaced to a keyboard that operates on two AAA batteries
 which last for about 2 years in normal operation.
 We log details of any instance when any key is pressed or released.
 The current version is the 4th generation of hardware and we have a fifth
 generation planned.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Software: Software is deployed at multiple levels.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Embedded software provides the hooks for us to interface with the keyboard.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Interfacing software is written in C and provides low level access to the
 data streams
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Application software is written in Perl and provides the interface for managemen
t of the feedback devices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Representation and analysis is done in R and generates the graphics that
 are displayed for the students after they have responded to a question.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Description
Distribution
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Hardware: If multiple schools are being catered for, then a centralized
 studio will be required to broadcast content to multiple locations.
 However, control signals will also need to be broadcast to permit the opportuni
ty for students keyboards to be activated.
 This process will also require a server in the classroom.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Initial Pilot Program in Maths
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2010, I decided to conduct a Pilot Program to measure the effectiveness
 of the process we had defined for improving government schools.
 As working with government is a complex process we decided to work with
 the Maria Niketan School in Bangalore which caters to the needs of the
 economically deprived.
 The results of that 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "work"
target "www.agem.in/pdf/BriefReport.pdf"

\end_inset

 convinced me that a process of low profile injection for 5 hours a week
 would be adequate to make government schools the preferred schools for
 80% of participating communities.
 This represents a low profile approach to reform which does not face the
 inherent resistance of the current system.
 This resistance is greater in government schools though it is significant
 also in private schools.
\end_layout

